00:15:31,137 --> 00:15:34,624
What's wrong with that one? That's one
of them little Charlie Brown trees.

234
00:15:34,724 --> 00:15:36,576
He's so cute.

235
00:15:38,102 --> 00:15:41,205
I like the smell of Mommy
and Victor's better.

236
00:15:43,524 --> 00:15:47,336
And it doesn't have
enough room for presents.

237
00:15:48,071 --> 00:15:52,383
Why don't you and me go shopping
for a big old Christmas tree?

238
00:15:52,867 --> 00:15:54,760
Cool beans!

239
00:15:55,870 --> 00:15:57,313
Can I have this one?

240
00:15:57,413 --> 00:16:00,942
It's almost as big as the one that
Mommy and Victor have at their house.

241
00:16:01,042 --> 00:16:04,445
Yeah, but, honey, that thing's $300.
I mean, that's crazy.

242
00:16:04,545 --> 00:16:08,357
For $300 it ought to already
have presents underneath it.

243
00:16:09,092 --> 00:16:11,953
Sugar, picking a Christmas tree
is like picking a boyfriend.

244
00:16:12,053 --> 00:16:14,414
Trust me. You can't just
settle on the first one.

245
00:16:14,514 --> 00:16:17,250
Or the second one or the third
or the fourth or the fifth.

246
00:16:17,350 --> 00:16:21,879
Okay, I get it, Dad.
Hey, can I get apple cider?

247
00:16:21,979 --> 00:16:24,924
I'll tell you what, that's the
best idea I've heard all day.

248
00:16:25,024 --> 00:16:28,052
Here you go.
Get me one if it's not $300.

249
00:16:28,152 --> 00:16:29,420
Okay.

250
00:16:34,492 --> 00:16:36,844
So you like what you see?

251
00:16:39,747 --> 00:16:41,599
I plead the Fifth.

252
00:16:41,958 --> 00:16:45,111
- Well, we have a wide variety of trees here.
- I see.

253
00:16:45,211 --> 00:16:47,530
If you want a fir tree,
we've got Douglas fir...

254
00:16:47,630 --> 00:16:51,159
we've got noble fir, we've got
concolor fir, we've got Canaan fir.

255
00:16:51,259 --> 00:16:56,122
- Hey, you look more like a pine guy to me.
- Do I look like a pine guy?

256
00:16:56,222 --> 00:17:01,002
Here I thought I was more of a concolor.
Boy, all these years I've been living a lie.

257
00:17:01,102 --> 00:17:03,922
Well, we have white pine,
Virginia pine and Scotch pine.

258
00:17:04,022 --> 00:17:08,509
- So, what's your pleasure?
- I want something very special and cheap.

259
00:17:08,609 --> 00:17:09,877
- Special and cheap?
- Yeah.

260
00:17:10,194 --> 00:17:13,932
Well, the ones that are cheaper
tend to be on the more sparse side.

261
00:17:14,032 --> 00:17:17,435
- But you can cover it up if you flock it.
- Flock?

262
00:17:17,535 --> 00:17:20,012
This one right here is only $165.

263
00:17:20,788 --> 00:17:22,357
Hundred and sixty-five dollars.

264
00:17:22,457 --> 00:17:25,276
- How much is the flocking?
- Oh, the flocking's free.

265
00:17:25,376 --> 00:17:28,488
You know what?
I'll just take the flocking.

266
00:17:28,588 --> 00:17:32,233
You could go for this guy over here.
He might be more in your price range.

267
00:17:32,800 --> 00:17:36,204
What in tarnation is that thing?

268
00:17:36,304 --> 00:17:41,542
That is a special-order 50-foot
Norway spruce shipped from Maine.

269
00:17:41,642 --> 00:17:44,754
- Fifty-foot.
- It costs $10,000.

270
00:17:44,854 --> 00:17:47,048
Ten thousand dollars.

271
00:17:47,148 --> 00:17:50,918
What kind of blockhead buys a
Christmas tree for $10,000?

272
00:17:52,028 --> 00:17:55,256
- Okay. Yeah, yeah. That's great.
- Never mind.

273
00:17:56,240 --> 00:17:58,768
Can you give me a second?
I wanna check that tree out.

274
00:17:58,868 --> 00:18:01,387
- Sure.
- That's something else.

275
00:18:03,664 --> 00:18:07,268
You couldn't find anything bigger?
Just kidding. Thank you very much.

276
00:18:07,669 --> 00:18:09,779
It's fantastic.

277
00:18:09,879 --> 00:18:11,272
Hey, Trish.

278
00:18:11,714 --> 00:18:15,577
Oh, it's perfect. Noel's gonna love it.
It's gonna be the best tree lighting ever.

279
00:18:15,677 --> 00:18:19,414
Victor, I get that Baxter Box always hosts
the town's tree-lighting ceremony...

280
00:18:19,514 --> 00:18:23,042
but do you really have to buy
the town a $10,000 tree?

281
00:18:23,142 --> 00:18:24,877
Are you trying to run for mayor?

282
00:18:24,977 --> 00:18:28,756
No, no, hon. I'm just trying to buy
some goodwill and affection here.

283
00:18:28,856 --> 00:18:32,927
I just figure the bigger the tree,
the more the affection, right?

284
00:18:33,027 --> 00:18:35,340
Oh, so he's trying to buy Noel's love.

285
00:18:35,440 --> 00:18:38,016
My little girl's love ain't
for sale for anybody.

286
00:18:38,116 --> 00:18:39,225
Sorry.

287
00:18:39,325 --> 00:18:44,639
Hey! No, I'm in here!
Turn it off! I can't see!

288
00:18:45,039 --> 00:18:48,276
Turn it off! Somebody
turn that machine off!

289
00:18:48,376 --> 00:18:50,645
I can't... I can't...

290
00:18:56,175 --> 00:18:58,820
Dad. What happened?

291
00:18:59,971 --> 00:19:02,740
I hope somebody got the
license plate of that pigeon.

292
00:19:04,142 --> 00:19:07,787
You wanna have a snowball fight?
Come on.

293
00:19:18,781 --> 00:19:21,676
You missed me.

294
00:19:22,452 --> 00:19:23,928
No, no, no.

295
00:19:24,829 --> 00:19:27,515
You have got a really good arm.

296
00:19:32,754 --> 00:19:35,189
Gotcha. Oh, she's charging.

297
00:19:36,591 --> 00:19:38,151
No! Okay, this is war.

298
00:19:40,261 --> 00:19:41,988
- Way to go.
- You missed me.

299
00:19:48,394 --> 00:19:50,463
I'm gonna feel this in the morning.

300
00:19:50,563 --> 00:19:53,291
How are you even doing that?

301
00:19:56,944 --> 00:19:59,681
I hit you a hundred times.

302
00:19:59,781 --> 00:20:03,217
I got you a million and 98.

303
00:20:05,620 --> 00:20:08,485
- You two have fun?
- We had tons of fun.

304
00:20:08,585 --> 00:20:10,608
I totally nailed Victor.

305
00:20:10,708 --> 00:20:12,151
- She did.
- Good for you.

306
00:20:12,251 --> 00:20:14,988
Well, your lunch is ready
for you in the kitchen.

307
00:20:15,088 --> 00:20:18,449
And remember, we're dropping
you off at your dad's at 3.

308
00:20:18,549 --> 00:20:21,536
We have enough time for another
snowball fight after lunch.

309
00:20:21,636 --> 00:20:22,862
Right, Victor?

310
00:20:23,513 --> 00:20:26,240
You wouldn't be interested
in peace talks, would you?

311
00:20:26,724 --> 00:20:29,711
Not a chance.

312
00:20:29,811 --> 00:20:32,079
I had a lot of fun with you, Victor.

313
00:20:36,025 --> 00:20:37,418
Me too.

314
00:20:37,694 --> 00:20:41,088
You're almost as much fun as my dad.

315
00:20:45,326 --> 00:20:48,054
Almost as much fun as Larry.

316
00:20:52,333 --> 00:20:53,935
I can't compete with that guy.

317
00:20:56,129 --> 00:21:00,408
Skating, sledding, hockey, ice fishing.

318
00:21:00,508 --> 00:21:03,036
He's like a big squishy teddy bear.

319
00:21:03,136 --> 00:21:07,498
This isn't a competition, Victor.
You're Noel's dad too.

320
00:21:07,598 --> 00:21:11,377
Dad Number 2. Second best. Runner-up.

321
00:21:11,477 --> 00:21:13,663
A substitute.

322
00:21:14,355 --> 00:21:17,416
Not the real thing but
a startling simulation.

323
00:21:17,859 --> 00:21:21,220
"Dad too," as in "dad also."

324
00:21:21,320 --> 00:21:25,299
Your job is to be there
for Noel, same as Larry.

325
00:21:26,242 --> 00:21:28,052
That's all that matters.

326
00:21:28,661 --> 00:21:30,346
Okay?

327
00:21:34,125 --> 00:21:36,653
Okay?

328
00:21:36,753 --> 00:21:38,771
Teddy bear.

329
00:21:42,675 --> 00:21:44,202
I'm telling you, Claude...

330
00:21:44,302 --> 00:21:47,622
Victor may have a snow machine,
but Noel is gonna love this.

331
00:21:47,722 --> 00:21:51,951
- Larry, this is crazy.
- Yeah, but it's the real-good kind of crazy.

332
00:21:52,643 --> 00:21:55,788
Who needs a snow machine
when you've got real snow?

333
00:21:56,939 --> 00:21:59,667
Go like this. It's better on your back.

334
00:22:06,074 --> 00:22:09,936
- When is he gonna be here?
- I'm sure he'll be here soon, honey.

335
00:22:10,036 --> 00:22:11,679
Hopefully in the next year.

336
00:22:12,497 --> 00:22:14,232
That's Larry.

337
00:22:14,332 --> 00:22:16,100
There he is.

338
00:22:18,252 --> 00:22:21,397
- Hey.
- Hey. He's here.

339
00:22:24,592 --> 00:22:27,862
- Hi, Daddy.
- Where's my little girl?

340
00:22:30,431 --> 00:22:33,334
Oh, good. Oh, you're getting big.

341
00:22:33,434 --> 00:22:36,129
We've been waiting for a half hour.
Where have you been?

342
00:22:36,229 --> 00:22:40,091
- I got a surprise for Noel.
- A surprise? What is it? What is it?

343
00:22:40,191 --> 00:22:43,136
How would you like to have
some real snow at Christmas?

344
00:22:43,236 --> 00:22:47,473
- We already have snow at Victor's.
- I know, but that's that fake stuff.

345
00:22:47,573 --> 00:22:50,393
I mean real snow. This come out
of the sky and everything.

346
00:22:50,493 --> 00:22:54,022
It's real snow, not that synthetic
man-made polyester stuff...

347
00:22:54,122 --> 00:22:55,732
that you've got at your house.

348
00:22:55,832 --> 00:22:58,860
- This is real.
- That would be awesome.

349
00:22:58,960 --> 00:23:01,863
- Darn right it would be.
- Let's show these nonbelievers, Lar.

350
00:23:01,963 --> 00:23:05,700
Oh, boy. It's gonna be exciting.
This is the best idea I ever had.

351
00:23:05,800 --> 00:23:07,735
Get ready to be bowled over.

352
00:23:15,393 --> 00:23:17,745
- Anybody got a towel?
- Daddy?

353
00:23:21,232 --> 00:23:23,176
- You know what that is?
- No.

354
00:23:23,276 --> 00:23:24,752
It's a tickle monster.

355
00:23:26,487 --> 00:23:28,014
It's a tickle monster.

356
00:23:28,114 --> 00:23:31,300
All right, you goof, time for bed.

357
00:23:31,993 --> 00:23:35,229
Good night, Dad. Thanks for the snow.

358
00:23:35,329 --> 00:23:39,567
I really liked it, even though
it was melted and everything.

359
00:23:39,667 --> 00:23:42,687
Sweetie, that's nice of you.
I appreciate it.

360
00:23:44,172 --> 00:23:47,742
Listen, I love you. Good night. Now,
you have a good night's sleep, okay?

361
00:23:47,842 --> 00:23:50,945
- Good night, Daddy.
- Good night, sweetie.

362
00:24:00,813 --> 00:24:03,508
I don't know, Claude.
I just can't catch a break.

363
00:24:03,608 --> 00:24:06,511
I don't know how I can
compete with Victor.

364
00:24:06,611 --> 00:24:08,638
It's tough. I'll give you that.

365
00:24:08,738 --> 00:24:11,975
He's younger, richer, more educated.

366
00:24:12,075 --> 00:24:14,978
He's in great shape and much,
much, much better-looking.

367
00:24:15,078 --> 00:24:17,472
All right. I get the point.

368
00:24:17,872 --> 00:24:19,649
But the more important question is...

369
00:24:19,749 --> 00:24:22,151
why do you feel the need
to compete with Victor?

370
00:24:22,251 --> 00:24:26,739
Noel doesn't care about that stuff.
She loves you for you, Larry.

371
00:24:26,839 --> 00:24:28,065
I am pretty lovable.

372
00:24:30,051 --> 00:24:31,944
Good night, Larry.

373
00:24:33,179 --> 00:24:35,281
See you later, Claude.

374
00:24:42,897 --> 00:24:46,092
- Is my angel ready to order?
- I sure am.

375
00:24:46,192 --> 00:24:49,504
- I was referring to the little angel.
- Oh, sorry.

376
00:24:49,779 --> 00:24:52,390
My usual, Maggie, please.

377
00:24:52,490 --> 00:24:55,468
PB & J, light on the
PB and heavy on the J.

378
00:24:56,369 --> 00:24:59,639
- Correct.
- I'll have the same thing I always have too.

379
00:25:00,081 --> 00:25:02,350
Deep-fried everything, hold the salad.

380
00:25:03,751 --> 00:25:06,738
I tell you what, Maggie,
you know me pretty good.

381
00:25:06,838 --> 00:25:09,357
I got your number, Larry.

382
00:25:12,844 --> 00:25:15,121
So, what you working on there?
Your homework?

383
00:25:15,221 --> 00:25:16,748
My letter to Santa.

384
00:25:16,848 --> 00:25:19,700
Letter to Santa? I thought
you got that done July 4th.

385
00:25:21,519 --> 00:25:24,339
There's something special I want.

386
00:25:24,439 --> 00:25:28,593
- What is it?
- I can't tell you or anyone else.

387
00:25:28,693 --> 00:25:33,348
If I do, it won't come true.
It's like making a wish.

388
00:25:33,448 --> 00:25:36,893
No, no, no. Don't worry.
I'm not gonna ruin that.

389
00:25:36,993 --> 00:25:39,220
But, hey, can you give me a little hint?

390
00:25:40,455 --> 00:25:42,815
I'm asking Santa...

391
00:25:42,915 --> 00:25:50,022
for the one thing I want more
than anything in the world.

392
00:25:50,631 --> 00:25:55,203
Well, hey, I got an idea.
There's a mailbox right over there.

393
00:25:55,303 --> 00:25:59,666
Why don't you give me the letter,
and then I'll run it out there?

394
00:25:59,766 --> 00:26:02,034
Would you, Daddy? Thank you so much.

395
00:26:02,352 --> 00:26:05,621
You got it, squirt. I'll be right back.

396
00:26:14,989 --> 00:26:16,391
Hey, Larry.

397
00:26:16,491 --> 00:26:19,060
- Hey, Claude, what's going on?
- What you up to?

398
00:26:19,160 --> 00:26:21,396
Noel's letter to Santa Claus.

399
00:26:21,496 --> 00:26:24,932
I figure what Victor can do
in quantity, I can do in quality.

400
00:26:25,416 --> 00:26:28,611
What? You're not thinking
of opening that, are you?

401
00:26:28,711 --> 00:26:30,772
Yeah. Of course.

402
00:26:31,506 --> 00:26:35,034
I mean, look, Victor can get a big old
tree and a bunch of fancy lights...

403
00:26:35,134 --> 00:26:37,412
and a bunch of fake snow.

404
00:26:37,512 --> 00:26:40,498
But when I see what she's got
in here, what she really wants...

405
00:26:40,598 --> 00:26:42,083
I can give it to her.

406
00:26:42,183 --> 00:26:45,411
That's a private letter,
not addressed to you.

407
00:26:45,853 --> 00:26:48,206
Not to mention, that's a federal crime.

408
00:26:49,399 --> 00:26:53,052
Claude, it's my daughter's
letter to Santa Claus.

409
00:26:53,152 --> 00:26:54,796
I think we're gonna be fine.

410
00:26:55,238 --> 00:26:58,266
That's just wrong. Wrong, wrong, wrong.

411
00:26:58,366 --> 00:27:01,269
And you see this? This is
my letter to Santa Claus.

412
00:27:01,369 --> 00:27:04,939
If I find out you tampered with it,
you're gonna answer to me...

413
00:27:05,039 --> 00:27:06,474
and Mr. Claus himself.

414
00:27:12,380 --> 00:27:15,399
Boy, who pooped in his hashbrowns?

415
00:27:38,531 --> 00:27:40,842
Boy, her handwriting's horrible.

416
00:27:41,409 --> 00:27:42,677
Just like her daddy's.

417
00:27:42,910 --> 00:27:46,981
"Dear Santa: For Christmas
I want my family to get...

418
00:27:47,081 --> 00:27:50,184
her... Hera...

419
00:27:52,295 --> 00:27:53,438
Herasone."

420
00:27:54,881 --> 00:27:57,358
What the heck's a herasone?

421
00:27:57,508 --> 00:28:01,487
- Bye-bye, Daddy.
- See you later, sweetheart.

422
00:28:04,807 --> 00:28:07,535
- So, what did you and Larry do today?
- Not much.

423
00:28:08,353 --> 00:28:13,374
- More ice fishing?
- No. We just went to the diner.

424
00:28:14,275 --> 00:28:17,628
- I wrote a letter to Santa.
- Let me guess.

425
00:28:18,279 --> 00:28:20,798
Pixie and her Starburst Buddies.

426
00:28:21,366 --> 00:28:23,643
Little Paris and her Magical Closet.

427
00:28:23,743 --> 00:28:26,220
Those are little-kid toys.

428
00:28:26,621 --> 00:28:29,691
Hold on. What...?

429
00:28:29,791 --> 00:28:31,109
What did you ask Santa for?

430
00:28:31,209 --> 00:28:34,696
I can't tell you, or else
I won't get what I want.

431
00:28:34,796 --> 00:28:36,355
I didn't even tell Dad.

432
00:28:37,799 --> 00:28:43,204
Well, you know, we should probably
mail those letters right away, so....

433
00:28:43,304 --> 00:28:46,240
- You know, I could take it for you.
- Dad already did.

434
00:28:47,225 --> 00:28:48,334
Did he?

435
00:28:48,434 --> 00:28:52,038
He went right out of the diner
to mail it as soon as I wrote it.

436
00:28:55,400 --> 00:28:56,542
Really?

437
00:28:58,695 --> 00:29:00,546
Thanks. Excuse me.

438
00:29:04,158 --> 00:29:05,518
Security. Welling here.

439
00:29:05,618 --> 00:29:07,145
Welling.

440
00:29:07,245 --> 00:29:09,263
I have an assignment for you.

441
00:29:13,292 --> 00:29:15,028
Yes, sir.

442
00:29:15,128 --> 00:29:17,480
It would be my pleasure, sir.

443
00:29:31,519 --> 00:29:33,788
What are you up to, chubby?

444
00:29:42,113 --> 00:29:45,266
Oh, hey. Hi, I'm Jeffrey.
Welcome to Toy Traders.

445
00:29:45,366 --> 00:29:48,269
Merry Christmas, happy holidays,
happy Hanukkah...

446
00:29:48,369 --> 00:29:51,230
happy Kwanzaa, and a very
happy winter solstice.

447
00:29:51,330 --> 00:29:54,234
- I think you got all the bases covered.
- Thank you.

448
00:29:54,334 --> 00:29:58,071
Listen. I'm looking for something,
but I don't quite know what I'm looking for.

449
00:29:58,171 --> 00:29:59,814
Okay.

450
00:30:00,882 --> 00:30:02,483
Herasone.

451
00:30:03,217 --> 00:30:06,120
I'm sorry. I'm having a hard
time reading your handwriting.

452
00:30:06,220 --> 00:30:08,915
That's not my handwriting.
It's my daughter's. She's 7.

453
00:30:09,015 --> 00:30:11,993
- Mine's a lot worse, trust me.
- Oh, it is?

454
00:30:13,353 --> 00:30:14,963
- Yeah.
- You have any of those?

455
00:30:15,063 --> 00:30:18,299
Yeah. No clue. No idea, sir.

456
00:30:18,399 --> 00:30:19,917
Oh, boy.

457
00:30:20,568 --> 00:30:22,920
Wait a second.
Unless she means Harrison.

458
00:30:23,571 --> 00:30:27,100
- What's a Harrison?
- Harrison the Talking Bear.

459
00:30:27,200 --> 00:30:30,561
You're gonna love this. Follow me. Yes!

460
00:30:30,661 --> 00:30:32,814
Harrison the Talking Bear.
Haven't you heard?

461
00:30:32,914 --> 00:30:37,819
It's only the most popular toy amongst the
coveted 5-to-10-year-old age demographic.

462
00:30:37,919 --> 00:30:41,606
So the bear learns the kids' names
and then says it back to them.

463
00:30:42,048 --> 00:30:43,825
It's the hottest toy this season.

464
00:30:43,925 --> 00:30:46,327
- Really? That bear?
- Oh, yeah. They love it.

465
00:30:46,427 --> 00:30:49,289
- That's what kids are going nuts over.
- Nuts for the bear.

466
00:30:49,389 --> 00:30:51,708
Well, all right. I guess
I'll get my daughter one.

467
00:30:51,808 --> 00:30:53,710
Sorry, but we're all sold out.

468
00:30:53,810 --> 00:30:57,589
These things keep flying off the
shelves as fast as we can stock them.

469
00:30:57,689 --> 00:31:01,926
My daughter really wants one of these bears.
